<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>There&#x2019;s also talk of reintroducing the Lord Howe Island phasmid&#x2014;a giant stick insect (or &#x2018;tree lobster&#x2019;) thought to be extinct since 1920 that was rediscovered in 2001 on Balls Pyramid, a dramatic volcanic stack 20 kilometers southeast of Lord Howe. However the mid-20th-century extinction of its natural predator, the Lord Howe boobook owl, has created a complication that could take scientists years to unravel.</p>

</article> </div>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
            <blockquote>
                <p>&#x201C;This has never been recorded in the human history of Lord Howe. Now we&#x2019;re seeing such dramatic changes so quickly, there&#x2019;s a risk that we could lose this forest really soon. And this is the only place like it in the world.&#x201D;</p>
<p class="quotee">Dean Hiscox, guide</p>            </blockquote>
    </article>
 </div>



<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>There&#x2019;s another whole world to discover underwater at Lord Howe, home to the world&#x2019;s southernmost barrier reef. Snorkeling in North Bay, I&#x2019;m awestruck by the diversity of marine life at this latitude; the island&#x2019;s location at the crossroads of <a href="https://lordhoweisland.info/blog/5-reasons-to-dive-australias-pristine-southern-most-coral-reef/">five major ocean currents</a> attracting a unique mix of tropical species near their southern limits and cooler-water species near their northern limits, as well as endemic subtropical species.</p>
<p>The diving is similarly spectacular, putting me at eye-level with huge lobsters, bedazzled nudibranch and vibrant corals at two of more than 350 dive spots logged by local outfit Pro Dive.</p>

</article> </div>


