      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://adventure.com/francesco-piattelli-olive-oil-farm-tuscany/</guid>
      <title>Ever just wanted to move to Tuscany and make olive oil? This New Yorker did just that</title>
      <flatplan:author name="Katie McKnoulty" role="author" url="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Contributor-bio-photo-Kate-McNoulty.jpg"/>
      <link>https://adventure.com/francesco-piattelli-olive-oil-farm-tuscany/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 20 Oct 2021 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <media:thumbnail url="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Hero-3-Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9338-francesco-piattelli-founder-agricola-maraviglia-scaled.jpg" caption=""/>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="content ps-gallery">


  <div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-3">

    </article>

    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 end">

<p><strong>Francesco Piattelli swapped his New York lifestyle to work on his family&#x2019;s olive farm in Tuscany. What&#x2019;s that like? Katie McKnoulty joins him during olive oil harvest season to find out.</strong><br><br>We&#x2019;re picking olives in a sun-drenched field overlooking the Tuscan countryside, a classic view of centuries-old hilltop towns and church spires. This view has barely changed in generations.<br><br>Although other things may have&#x2026; Francesco gets out his portable Bluetooth speaker and plays a track you might hear in a Brooklyn coffee shop. Noticing this paradoxical moment too, he turns to me and says, &#x201C;People sometimes look down on agricultural work but I mean, look how much fun we&#x2019;re having!&#x201D;<br><br>It&#x2019;s October and olive harvest time in Monte San Savino. I&#x2019;ve been invited to stay with 37-year-old Italian-American Francesco Piattelli and his partner, Francesca Gambato to experience and document the harvest of their 4.5 hectares of olive trees in the heart of the Toscano IGP denomination. They&#x2019;ve spent the last two years nurturing these olives to produce their organic, sustainable olive oil, <a href="https://agricolamaraviglia.net/">Agricola Maraviglia</a>, and they lead harvesting retreats on the side. They grow and harvest their olives using traditional Tuscan techniques&#x2014;small batch, hands-on and organic. With over 85 per cent of production coming from their restoration of local family-owned groves, they&#x2019;re helping to regenerate the local environment and keep the Tuscan olive oil economy and legacy alive.</p>
    </article>

   </div>



<figure>

<div class="row small-collapse small-up-1 medium-uncollapse"><div class="column featured-image"><img class="featured-image " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-1180x787.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-1180x787.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-1180x787.jpg 1180w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-500x333.jpg 500w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-768x512.jpg 768w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9464-countryside-surrounding-olive-grove-scaled.jpg 2560w" sizes="(max-width: 1180) 100vw, 1180" alt="The countryside surrounding the olive grove."></div>
</div>
    <figcaption class="row"><div class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">This view has barely changed in generations. Although other things may have&#x2026; Monte San Savino is where 37-year-old Italian-American Francesco Piattelli and his partner, Francesca Gambato run a 4.5 hectares of olive farm in the heart of the Toscano IGP denomination.
<span class="photographer override">Photo: Katie McKnoulty</span></div></figcaption>
</figure>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>But Francesco didn&#x2019;t always work with the land. Growing up in small-town Tuscany with an American mother and Italian father, he moved to New York City at 26 in search of bigger challenges. But seven years later, stressed out and unsatisfied, he left his life and his advertising agency to return to his homeland.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>RELATED: <a href="https://adventure.com/travel-for-good-without-travel">How travelers can be a force for good (without traveling anywhere)</a></strong></p>
<p><u></u>With his mother living in an apartment nearby and his father on a small sailboat in the Mediterranean, Francesco was able to transform his childhood home into <a href="https://www.maraviglia.net/">Maraviglia Conscious Living</a>, a retreat center where yogis and meditators could reconnect with nature and themselves.</p>
<p>This also gave him a chance to reconnect with his homeland and figure out his next steps. &#x201C;Living here, you see every season,&#x201D; he says. &#x201C;You see the trees. They bloom and they fall and the energy is just so palpable and so strong. The love for olives and nature came after. It&#x2019;s something that surprised me.&#x201D;</p>

</article> </div>


<figure>

<div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 "><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9075-francesco-piattelli-founder-agricola-maraviglia-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9075-francesco-piattelli-founder-agricola-maraviglia-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9075-francesco-piattelli-founder-agricola-maraviglia-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9075-francesco-piattelli-founder-agricola-maraviglia-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Francesco Piattelli holds onto one of the nets used for harvest."></div><div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 medium-up-2 img-block-col-2 "><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8952-2-fresh-green-olives-best-tasting-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8952-2-fresh-green-olives-best-tasting-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8952-2-fresh-green-olives-best-tasting-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8952-2-fresh-green-olives-best-tasting-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="A branch covered in green olives."></div><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9043-collecting-up-harvested-olives-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9043-collecting-up-harvested-olives-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9043-collecting-up-harvested-olives-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9043-collecting-up-harvested-olives-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Collecting up harvested olives."></div></div>
    <figcaption class="row"><div class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">&#x201C;If I&#x2019;m honest, I&#x2019;d imagined picking every olive one by one from each silvery-green branch and placing it in a woven basket slung over my arm,&#x201D; writes Katie McKnoulty. &#x201C;But that&#x2019;s not how it&#x2019;s done.&#x201D;
<span class="photographer override">Photos: Katie McKnoulty</span></div></figcaption>
</figure>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>On my first morning, we head out early to the olive groves. Francesco has gathered six friends and family<span style="font-weight: 400;">&#x2014;</span>serial harvesters<span style="font-weight: 400;">&#x2014;</span>to help pick olives eight hours a day for the five weeks of the harvest.</p>

</article> </div>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
            <blockquote>
                <p>There are even strategy meetings to decide how best to divest the trees of their bounty, as efficiently as possible, to get those early-harvest green olives that make the best-tasting olive oil.</p>
<p class="quotee"></p>            </blockquote>
    </article>
 </div>



<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>One friend, Magali, lives and works on a natural winery in the south of France with her partner, and travels for various harvests. Italian-American Sam lives locally with his family and helped set up the &#x2018;forest kindergarten&#x2019; that sees his little boy spend every day in nature.</p>
<p>I&#x2019;m equally awed and intimidated by these people living by values so at odds with the consumerist values rampant in cities that I&#x2019;ve known.</p>

</article> </div>


<figure>

<div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 "><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8806-hand-raking-olives-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8806-hand-raking-olives-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8806-hand-raking-olives-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-8806-hand-raking-olives-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Olives are hand raked by a worker."></div><div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 medium-up-2 img-block-col-2 "><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9082-harvested-olives-ready-to-be-pressed-into-oil-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9082-harvested-olives-ready-to-be-pressed-into-oil-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9082-harvested-olives-ready-to-be-pressed-into-oil-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9082-harvested-olives-ready-to-be-pressed-into-oil-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Harvested olives ready to be pressed into oil."></div><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9487-separating-olives-from-leaves-and-branches-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9487-separating-olives-from-leaves-and-branches-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9487-separating-olives-from-leaves-and-branches-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9487-separating-olives-from-leaves-and-branches-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Hands separate olives from the leaves and branches."></div></div>
    <figcaption class="row"><div class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">Most of the &#x2018;Italian&#x2019; olive oil we encounter comes from different farms around Europe. It&#x2019;s unusual to find olive oil from a single farm, like this one.
<span class="photographer override">Photos: Katie McKnoulty</span></div></figcaption>
</figure>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>It&#x2019;s my first harvest. If I&#x2019;m honest, I&#x2019;d imagined picking every olive one by one from each silvery-green branch and placing it in a woven basket slung over my arm. But that&#x2019;s not how it&#x2019;s done.</p>
<p>It&#x2019;s not so much picking the olives as it is shaking and combing the trees, and catching the falling olives on meters-long nets laid out below. There are even strategy meetings to decide how best to divest the trees of their bounty, as efficiently as possible, to get those early-harvest green olives that make the best-tasting olive oil. And we&#x2019;ve got 800 trees to cover.</p>

</article> </div>


<figure>

<div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 "><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9572-Magali-fixing-nets-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9572-Magali-fixing-nets-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9572-Magali-fixing-nets-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9572-Magali-fixing-nets-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="A man is bent down fixing a green net used for harvesting olives."></div><div class="row expanded collapse small-up-1 medium-up-2 img-block-col-2 "><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9986-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9986-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9986-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-katie-mcknoulty-agricola-maraviglia-monte-san-savino-tuscany-9986-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Olive pickers gather their harvest in large nets."></div><div class="column"><img class="gallery " data-lazy-src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-KA0A651-1920x1080.jpg" src="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-KA0A651-1920x1080.jpg" srcset="https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-KA0A651-1920x1080.jpg 1920w, https://adventure.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Olive-Oil-KA0A651-1180x664.jpg 1180w" sizes="(max-width: 3840) 100vw, 3840" alt="Frabcesco prepares sausages for lunch out on the property while workers rest on a truck nearby."></div></div>
    <figcaption class="row"><div class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">Top: Magali fixes the nets which are used to harvest olives; Middle: Olive pickers gather their harvest in large nets; Bottom: Francesco prepares sausages for an al fresco lunch.
<span class="photographer override">Photos: Katie McKnoulty</span></div></figcaption>
</figure>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>Of these 800 trees, only 100 are Francesco&#x2019;s; the rest are on loan from local families. Generations past felt connected to these olive trees, seeing them as their duty, not to mention an extra income. But today, with the sorry price the oil commands and younger generations no longer maintaining the trees or simply moving&#xA0; away, many groves around Monte San Savino sit abandoned.</p>

</article> </div>


<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
            <blockquote>
                <p>&#x201C;In the supermarkets and even in gourmet stores, it&#x2019;s really rare to find olive oil from one single farm.&#x201D;</p>
<p class="quotee">Francesco Piattelli</p>            </blockquote>
    </article>
 </div>



<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>&#x201C;They were wonderfully taken care of up to five years ago. Now, they&#x2019;re just full of thorns,&#x201D; Francesco tells me. &#x201C;I take over and restore them. Either by paying these families, if they know how to do it, or I take care of them myself. I prune them, I clean them, I pick them, I press them, and I give them a percentage.&#x201D;</p>

</article> </div>


