<div>
    <article class="columns small-12 medium-6 medium-offset-3">
        <p>The next day, we eat lunch together around a long table at the farmhouse. Francesca cuts the radicchio and goat&#x2019;s cheese quiche fresh out of the oven and dresses the fresh green salad with lashings of olive oil. It&#x2019;s all made by her hand, using ingredients taken just hours ago from their bountiful garden, a hundred meters from where we sit.</p>
<p>I have a new appreciation for this amber liquid sitting on the table. It&#x2019;s not just the delicious oil itself. It&#x2019;s everything it represents.&#xA0;It&#x2019;s a way of living, working, consuming that works with the planet and the people, not against them.</p>
<p>It may be just a bottle of olive oil made by one man, on a small farm in a tiny corner of the world, but it&#x2019;s pointing us in the right direction.</p>

</article> </div>






